# Implementing a Sidebar Toggle in Phoenix LiveView Without Server Roundtrip

To implement a sidebar with a toggle button in Phoenix LiveView without making a roundtrip to the server, you'll want to use client-side JavaScript hooks. Here's a step-by-step guide:

## 1. Set Up the LiveView Component

First, create your LiveView with the sidebar structure:

```elixir
defmodule MyAppWeb.PageLive do
  use MyAppWeb, :live_view

  def mount(_params, _session, socket) do
    {:ok, assign(socket, sidebar_open: true)}
  end

  def render(assigns) do
    ~H"""
    <div class="layout" id="layout-container" phx-hook="Sidebar">
      <div class="toggle-button" id="sidebar-toggle">
        <button>Toggle Sidebar</button>
      </div>

      <div class="sidebar" id="sidebar" data-open={@sidebar_open}>
        <!-- Sidebar content -->
        <ul>
          <li>Menu Item 1</li>
          <li>Menu Item 2</li>
          <li>Menu Item 3</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="main-content">
        <!-- Main content -->
        <h1>Main Content Area</h1>
        <p>This is the main content of your application.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    """
  end
end
```

## 2. Create the JavaScript Hook

In your `assets/js/hooks.js` file (create it if it doesn't exist):

```javascript
const Hooks = {}

Hooks.Sidebar = {
  mounted() {
    const sidebar = document.getElementById('sidebar')
    const toggleBtn = document.getElementById('sidebar-toggle')

    toggleBtn.addEventListener('click', () => {
      // Toggle a class for CSS transitions/animations
      sidebar.classList.toggle('open')

      // If you want to maintain state between page refreshes
      // You can optionally store the state in localStorage
      const isOpen = sidebar.classList.contains('open')
      localStorage.setItem('sidebar_open', isOpen)
    })

    // Restore state from localStorage on page load (optional)
    if (localStorage.getItem('sidebar_open') === 'true') {
      sidebar.classList.add('open')
    } else if (localStorage.getItem('sidebar_open') === 'false') {
      sidebar.classList.remove('open')
    }
  }
}

export default Hooks
```

## 3. Register the Hook

In your main JavaScript file (usually `assets/js/app.js`):

```javascript
import {Socket} from "phoenix"
import {LiveSocket} from "phoenix_live_view"
import topbar from "../vendor/topbar"
import Hooks from "./hooks"

let csrfToken = document.querySelector("meta[name='csrf-token']").getAttribute("content")
let liveSocket = new LiveSocket("/live", Socket, {
  params: {_csrf_token: csrfToken},
  hooks: Hooks
})

// Connect if there are any LiveViews on the page
liveSocket.connect()

// ...rest of your app.js
```

## 4. Add CSS

In your CSS file (e.g., `assets/css/app.css`):

```css
.layout {
  display: flex;
  min-height: 100vh;
}

.sidebar {
  width: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  transition: width 0.3s ease;
  background-color: #333;
  color: white;
}

.sidebar.open {
  width: 250px;
}

.main-content {
  flex: 1;
  padding: 20px;
}

.toggle-button {
  position: fixed;
  top: 10px;
  left: 10px;
  z-index: 100;
}
```

## 5. Optional: Syncing Client-Side State with Server (if needed)

If you want to synchronize the sidebar state with the server (for example, to persist it across page navigations), you can use `phx-click` with `js-push` instead of the hook approach:

```elixir
def render(assigns) do
  ~H"""
  <div class="layout">
    <div class="toggle-button">
      <button phx-click={JS.push("toggle_sidebar")}>Toggle Sidebar</button>
    </div>

    <div class={"sidebar #{if @sidebar_open, do: "open"}"}>
      <!-- Sidebar content -->
    </div>

    <div class="main-content">
      <!-- Main content -->
    </div>
  </div>
  """
end

def handle_event("toggle_sidebar", _, socket) do
  {:noreply, assign(socket, sidebar_open: !socket.assigns.sidebar_open)}
end
```

## Summary

This implementation allows you to toggle the sidebar entirely on the client side without making any server roundtrips. The hook handles the toggle functionality, and CSS transitions provide a smooth open/close animation.
